The Examine  lets you inspect an operator's python storage, locals, globals, expressions, and extensions.
examineDAT_Class

Contents
 
 
 
 
 
 





  op -  to the operator to examine.


		
  source -  - Specifies what part of the operator to examine.

 storage - Examine the operator's storage. locals - Examine the local dictionary associated with the operator's module. (DATs only). extensions - Examine any extension objects defined in the . globals - Examine the global dictionary associated with the project (accessible via the textport). expression - Specify the object to be examined.
		
  subkey - If the object to be examined is a dictionary you can specify which element to examine here.


		
  expression - When source is set to , enter your expression in this parameter.


		
  level - Clamp the maximum depth level.


		
  key - Filter Key results.


		
  type - Filter Type results.


		
  value - Filter Value results.


		
  expandclasses - When true, complex object structures (example ) are further expanded.


		
  maxlevels - Specify the maximum depth in which to expand a python object.


		
  format -  - Determines whether the output is raw text or in table format.

 text - table -
		
  outputheaders - Turn this on to display the column names when Format is set to Table.


		
  outputlevel - Turn this on to output the Level column of the results.


		
  outputkey - Turn this on to output the Key column of the results.


		
  outputtype - Turn this on to output the Type column of the results.


		
  outputvalue - Turn this on to output the Value column of the results.





  language -  - Select how the  decides which script language to operate on.

 input - The  uses the inputs script language. node - The  uses it's own script language.

  extension -  - Select the file extension this  should expose to external editors.

 dat - various common file extensions. language - pick extension from DATs script language. custom - Specify a custom extension.

  customext - Specifiy the custom extension.



  wordwrap -  - Enable Word Wrap for Node Display.

 input - The  uses the inputs setting. on - Turn on Word Wrap. off - Turn off Word Wrap.



Extra Information for the Examine  can be accessed via an Info CHOP.



 - Number of rows in this . - Number of columns in this .
 - Number of times the operator has cooked since the process started. - Duration of the last cook in milliseconds. - Frame number when this operator was last cooked relative to the component timeline. - Frame number when this operator was last cooked relative to the absolute time. - Time in milliseconds at which the operator started cooking in the frame it was cooked. - Time in milliseconds at which the operator finished cooking in the frame it was cooked. - 1 if operator was cooked this frame. - Number of warnings in this operator if any. - Number of errors in this operator if any.

DATs
• • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • 

An Operator Family that manipulates text strings: multi-line text or tables. Multi-line text is often a python Script or GLSL Shader, but can be any multi-line text. Tables are rows and columns of cells, each containing a text string.



Any of the procedural data operators. OPs do all the work in TouchDesigner. They "cook" and output data to other OPs, which ultimately result in new images, data and audio being generated. See Node.



The location of an operator within the TouchDesigner environment, for example, /geo1/circle1, a node called circle1 in a component called geo1. The path / is called Root. This path is displayed at the top of every Pane, showing which Component's network you are currently in. To refer instead to a filesystem folder, directory, disk file or http: address, see Folder.



Storage is a python dictionary in each operator, where users can store and fetch extra data.



Any component can be extended with its own Python classes which contain python functions and data.



An Operator Family that contains its own Network. There are sixteen 3D Object Component and ten 2D Panel Component types. See also Network Path.



A text string that contains data (string, float, list, boolean, etc.) and operators (+ * < etc) that are evaluated by the node's language (python or Tscript) and returns a string, float list or boolean, etc. Expressions are used in parameters, DATs and in scripts.



Any of the procedural data operators. OPs do all the work in TouchDesigner. They "cook" and output data to other OPs, which ultimately result in new images, data and audio being generated. See Node.



The generic thing that holds an Operator, and includes Flags (display, bypass, lock, render, immune) and its position/size in the network. Whether you "lay down an Operator" or "lay down an Node", you're doing the same thing.



An Operator Family which operate on Channels (a sequence of numbers (Samples)) which are used for animation, audio, mathematics, simulation, logic, UI construction, and data streamed from/to devices and protocols.
